{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17600426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17600426"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:03:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:03:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15614"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15614"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.31,0.04,0.12,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8305"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114388"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8305"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96389"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7001"},{"type":"tags","id":"7004"},{"type":"tags","id":"7555"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20048"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22674"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114388"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe optic chiasm is a critical anatomical structure in the visual pathway.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes it\u0027s anatomical location?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior to the anterior commissure and posterior to the lamina terminalis","Inferior to the pituitary gland and superior to the sphenoid sinus","Lateral to the cavernous sinus and medial to the internal carotid artery","Superior to the hypothalamus and inferior to the corpus callosum","Superior to the pituitary gland and inferior to the hypothalamus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe optic chiasm is located in the anterior cranial fossa. It sits \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior to the pituitary gland and inferior to the hypothalamus\u003C/strong\u003E. This position makes it vulnerable to compression from pituitary tumours growing superiorly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe chiasm is not \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior to the pituitary gland and superior to the sphenoid sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - this would place it too low. It is not \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior to the hypothalamus and inferior to the corpus callosum\u003C/strong\u003E - this would place it too high. It is not \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral to the cavernous sinus and medial to the internal carotid artery\u003C/strong\u003E - this describes a more lateral position. It is not \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior to the anterior commissure and posterior to the lamina terminalis\u003C/strong\u003E - this would place it too anterior.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis anatomical position is clinically significant as expanding pituitary tumours can compress the chiasm, leading to characteristic visual field defects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The optic chiasm is located in the anterior cranial fossa, superior to the pituitary gland and inferior to the hypothalamus.","The optic chiasm is where the nasal (medial) retinal fibres from each eye cross to the opposite side."],"references":["Ireland AC, Carter IB. Neuroanatomy, Optic Chiasm. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK542287/","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96389"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15614"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96389"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-16T10:09:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-16T10:09:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8305"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114388"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount"